1 (a) The number of incidents involving the use of force involving the use of:
2 (1) A baton;
3 (2) A chemical agent; or
4 (3) An electronic stun device.
5 (b) For each incident described in paragraph (a):
6 (1) The location of the incident, including, without limitation, whether
7 the incident occurred:
8 (I) On or in the grounds, property, buildings or any other facility of
9 the school district or charter school; or
10 (II) A location other than the grounds, property, buildings or any
11 other facility of the school district or charter school;
12 (2) Whether the incident occurred during the school day or at an activity
13 or event sponsored by the school district or charter school; and
14 (3) Except as otherwise provided in this subparagraph, the rank of each
15 school police officer who used such force and the number of years that each such
16 school police officer has been employed. The provisions of this subparagraph
17 only apply to the report required of the board of trustees of a school district that
18 employs more than 75 school police officers.
19 (c) The demographic information, including, without limitation, age, race,
20 gender and ethnicity, of the persons upon whom such force was used by school
21 police. All information must be reported in the aggregate and must not include
22 any personally identifiable information.
23 3. As used in this section:
24 (a) “Baton” means a cylindrical instrument that is designed to deliver a
25 blunt force contact or a strike to a person in close proximity.
26 (b) “Chemical agent” means any chemical which can rapidly produce
27 sensory irritation or disabling physical effects in humans, which disappear within
28 a short time following termination of exposure. The term includes, without
29 limitation, items commonly referred to as tear gas, pepper spray, pepper balls and
30 oleoresin capsicum.
31 (c) “Electronic stun device” means a device that:
32 (1) Emits an electrical charge or current that is transmitted by projectile,
33 physical contact or other means; and
34 (2) Is designed to disable a person or animal temporarily or permanently.
35 (d) “School police officer” [includes] means a peace officer who [is
36 employed] :
37 (1) Is employed by [a metropolitan police department created pursuant to
38 chapter 280] the board of [NRS or a sheriff’s office that has] trustees of a school
39 district; or
40 (2) Provides services to a charter school pursuant to a contract entered
41 into [a contract] with the board of trustees of a school district [to provide police
42 services in public schools] pursuant to NRS [391.281.] 388A.384.
43 Sec. 2. (Deleted by amendment.)
44 Sec. 3. (Deleted by amendment.)
45 Sec. 4. (Deleted by amendment.)
46 Sec. 5. (Deleted by amendment.)
47 Sec. 5.5. The first report required pursuant to section 1 of this act:
48 1. Is due on or before the first day of the 2026-2027 school year; and
49 2. Must contain the information required pursuant to section 1 of this act for
50 the 2025-2026 school year.
51 Sec. 6. This act becomes effective on July 1, 2025.

